CNN Model for Disease Classification

The following describes my workflow and rationale for design of a supervised image classification CNN model for pneumonia diagnosis. The model takes in 2D BW images of chest x-rays and outputs as "pneumonia" or "non-pneumonia" label. I used tensorflow for python v3.10.(Dataset available on Kaggle and from https://ieeexplore.ieee.org/abstract/document/8741582)

Workflow:

Import and view data- I compressed images to speed up training and import time. Could possibly go back to this step and use non-compressed images to see how it affects accuracy.

Clean and Organize data- Some of the images were RGB instead of BW so I wrote a program to take care of this. After cleaning I made sure to visualize these images to make sure they looked right. I also put all of the images into an array suitable for the CNN.

Design the Network: The model was built in a similar way to what was published in the IEEE link, with blocks of convolution. However, I started with a less is more approach and played around with layer number and size, adding and tweaking things based on intuition.

Troubleshooting: Overfitting was a huge problem at first, so I added a few dropout steps. Adding the larger dense layer in between drop out steps really helped performance. I also had an issue of step sizes being too large so I scheduled the learning rate with exponential decay and it helped with fluidity and convergence.

Model Performance and Validation: I assessed accuracy and precision, and looked at confusion matrices of test and validation sets. If this model were to be used in diagnostics, very few pneumonia diagnoses would be missed. For the test set, 91.5% of pneumonia cases were labeled as such. However, there were more false positives than I would have liked, with 23% of negative cases being labeled positive. I believe this model is comparable to the one published with this dataset.

def rgb2gray(rgb):
    return np.dot(rgb[...,:3], [0.2989, 0.5870, 0.1140])

#write a function to rescale images to decrease computational demand
def scale_resize_image(image):
    #image=rgb2gray(image)
    image = image/255 
    image = resize(image, (imSize,imSize)) # Resizing the image to 224x224 dimension
    return (image)

Build the Model

In [226]:
#BEST ~91/83, with learning rate .00001, 15, 80 epochs, batch size 64. Converged at 93/85 (best test accuracy=86)
model = keras.models.Sequential([
keras.layers.Conv2D(3, 3, activation='relu',input_shape = [imSize,imSize,1]), #originally 3x3 kernel. 5x3 had 88% for LR .0001, 10?
keras.layers.Conv2D(5, 3, activation='relu',input_shape = [imSize,imSize,1]), #originally 3x3 kernel. 5x3 had 88% for LR .0001, 10?
keras.layers.Conv2D(5, 3, activation='relu',input_shape = [imSize,imSize,1]), #what happens if i duplicate?
tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4),
keras.layers.Flatten(),
keras.layers.Dense(90, activation = 'relu' ), #originally 128, 256 similar at ~85 for 3x3, 256 bad for 5x3
tf.keras.layers.Dropout(0.4),
keras.layers.Dense(32, activation = 'relu' ), #best 32
keras.layers.Dense(16, activation = 'relu' ), #best 32
keras.layers.Dense(16, activation = 'relu' ), #originally 16
keras.layers.Dense(2, activation = 'softmax' )])
model.summary()

Compile the Model

In [227]:
#compile the network

model.compile(loss = 'binary_crossentropy', #try SparseCategoricalCrossentropy was binary_crossentropy
    optimizer = 'adam',
    metrics = ['accuracy',tf.keras.metrics.Precision(name='precision')]) #

#set up exponential decay to schedule decreasing step sizes so that the model doesn't diverge
def exponential_decay(lr0, s):
    def exponential_decay_fn(epoch):
        return lr0 * 0.1 **(epoch / s)
    return exponential_decay_fn

exponential_decay_fn = exponential_decay(0.00001, 15) #first number is the initial learning rate, second number is the rate at which the learning rate decreases. Lower number = faster decrease

Fit the Model

In [228]:
#This took around 30 minutes to train
checkpoint_cb = tf.keras.callbacks.ModelCheckpoint("xray_model.h5",save_best_only=True)
early_stopping_cb = tf.keras.callbacks.EarlyStopping(monitor="val_accuracy",
                                                     patience=20, #the number of epochs that elapse without improvement
                                                     restore_best_weights=True)# plot history
lr_scheduler = tf.keras.callbacks.LearningRateScheduler(exponential_decay_fn)

#history = model.fit(trainX,y_train,epochs = 40,validation_data = (testX, y_test))
history = model.fit(trainX, trainY1,
                    epochs = 80,
                    validation_data = (testX, testY1),
                    batch_size=64, #added this at 64 because it kept getting stuck at .7429. 20 epochs finished around 80/100
                    callbacks=[lr_scheduler,early_stopping_cb,checkpoint_cb])

Final thoughts and Future Directions

Possible Areas of Improvement

Contrast: The contrast and white balance on the images seem to be quite variable. If I can normalize this somehow, it may improve model performance.

Segmentation: Radiological pneumonia diagnosis is made by noticing a "cloudiness" in the lungs, which are located in the center of these images. Therefore, the model likely "pays attention" to this location the most. Could segmentation allow for increased focus on this area and improvement in performance?

Recurrant NN?: Could I increase accuracy with recurrant layers?

Low Sample Size: This may be the best this particular model can do with such a low sample size. Increasing size of training dataset may improve performance
